<TEXT>
in the tumultuous aftermath of the cold war 
president bush and his nato colleagues gather in london this week 
to chart the political and military future of europe 
it is a meeting that none of them could have envisioned when 
nato leaders last met 13 months ago to toast the 40th anniversary 
of the military alliance four decades of keeping the soviet 
threat in check 
but drastic changes in eastern europe have wrought dramatic 
alterations in the wests military federation as well 
the central issue of the meeting slated for thursday and 
friday strikes at the very heart of the atlantic alliance 
how can nato after four decades as a military alliance poised 
against the warsaw pact transform itself into a mostly political 
organization following the collapse of communism in eastern europe 
on a related front the leaders must deal with soviet anxieties 
about east germany leaving the warsaw pact to join with west 
germany as one nation within nato bush is floating the idea of a 
nato statement of nonaggression toward nations of eastern and 
central europe 
and at the prompting of france and germany they will debate 
whether america and her allies should prop up soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachev and his crumbling economy bush does not like 
the idea of economic aid but leaders of the 12member european 
community already have agreed in principle to provide some form of 
financial help 
the politics of perestroika helps us all declared west 
german chancellor helmut kohl and french president francois 
mitterrand said gorbachevs success is in the interest of 
everyone 
bush told a news conference on friday it is hard for the 
american people to say why put xbillions of dollars of money into 
the soviet economy when its not reformed when theyre spending 18 
percent of their gross national product on military and when 
theyre spending an estimated 5 billion annually in cuba some 
of our allies might be as concerned about that last point as we 
are 
the heavy agenda of the nato meeting will spill over from london 
to houston where a smaller group of world leaders will meet at the 
annual economic summit of the seven largest industrialized nations 
eastwest relations and particularly the question of a 
financial bailout for moscow will dominate the threeday houston 
meeting trade disputes and environmental problems also will be on 
the agenda 
japan is expected to urge an easing of sanctions against china 
but the united states opposes that now an administration official 
said beijing must relax its stand against prodemocracy forces 
before any adjustment is warranted 
but it is the dramatic changes in europe that will dominate the 
london and houston agendas 
the berlin wall has fallen free elections have replaced most of 
the totalitarian leaders of eastern and central europe and red 
army troops and tanks are preparing to go home 
secretary of state james a baker iii said such change brings 
in its wake not only great hope but also great uncertainty and some 
danger 
bush is concerned that nato keep up its military guard albeit 
with reduced firepower as the soviet threat diminishes yet bush 
rejects the idea of getting rid of all nuclear weapons 
i dont want to make europe safe for conventional war baker 
said echoing comments by bush 
the secretary said nato would not abandon its longstanding 
flexible response strategy of threatening to fire nuclear 
weapons first in response to a major soviet attack with 
conventional forces 
the leaders are expected to order a review to develop a 
negotiating position for reducing shortrange nuclear weapons in 
talks with moscow the kremlin suggests that those negotiations 
begin this fall but nato insists that they take place only after 
an agreement to reduce tanks artillery and other conventional 
forces in europe 
nato chiefs are expected to nudge negotiators from the east and 
west to wrap up the slowmoving conventional arms talks and pledge 
to make even deeper cuts in a later round of discussions 
to ease moscows fears west germany has proposed to keep nato 
forces from what is now east germany for awhile and to allow the 
red army forces to remain during that transition period 
west germany also is offering moscow 3 billion in bank credits 
and urging the west to contribute funds toward an even bigger 
assistance package 
the funds are viewed by some as a payoff to the soviets to let 
east germany go this is ransom but its a very good way to do 
business said michael mandelbaum senior fellow at the council 
on foreign relations 
west germans credit gorbachev with kindling eastern european 
reforms particularly the longsought goal of german unification 
and they are concerned that a sinking economy might sink gorbachev 
as well 
the us view is that it would be a waste of money to pump funds 
into an ineffective statecontrolled economy baker suggested that 
the summit partners in houston should develop principles and 
guidelines for awarding aid to moscow but he acknowledged that 
some countries may not be satisfied with that 
it may be a case of each country going its own way baker 
said 
</TEXT>
