<TEXT>
just as mikhail s gorbachev gets his change to 
radically overhaul the communist partys rusty political machine 
conservatives are challenging his plans to rewrite the rules on who 
runs the soviet union 
conservative delegates will dominate the 28th communist party 
congress which opens monday and gorbachev may not win approval of 
the sweeping changes he envisions 
some conservatives even are demanding that he leave the top 
party job 
originally gorbachev viewed the congress as a means of cleaning 
out the kremlins old guard and last year he won approval to hold 
the congress a year early to hasten changes 
among the main tasks of the congress will be rewriting party 
rules to revamp what have traditionally been the most powerful 
soviet institutions 
the rules affect all 19 million members of the communist party 
down to local bosses and the rank and file and gorbachev says he 
wants changes to give the party a second wind 
the proposed changes include 
replacing the general secretary with a party chairman and 
first secretary 
renaming and expanding the partys top body the politburo 
thus diluting the power of each member 
nominating multiple candidates for party jobs 
restricting elected party officials to two terms 
the proposed rule changes were published thursday and gorbachev 
is expected to offer more details when he opens the congress monday 
with a threehour report 
he also wants to press his drive to redirect the partys energy 
from managing the economy toward more general policysetting and 
to transfer management responsibilities to the government 
but because gorbachev has introduced a measure of democracy into 
the party he has lost some control over its decisions 
conservatives can push their own agenda yegor ligachev a 
politburo hardliner has said renewal means the fixing of 
boundaries and the cleansing from the party of all those who are 
destroying it who are engaging in a factional oppositional 
struggle and who are participating in antisocialist movements 
the most important proposed rule changes would affect the 
249member central committee the partys policymaking body the 
committee is a bastion of conservative holdovers elected under the 
late leonid i brezhnev party chief from 19641982 
the congress will elect a new central committee gorbachev had 
one previous chance to win control of the committee at the 1986 
congress but had been in office only 11 months and did not have 
enough power 
politburo member lev zaikov has said 90 percent of the central 
committee members should be replaced by younger people 
the soviet weekly arguments and facts analyzed the committee in 
february and found that 61 percent of the members were at or beyond 
retirement age 60 more than half the members were elected from 
1961 to 1981 just 29 workers and peasants sit on the committee 
despite the partys claim to represent those those classes 
there are sizable blocs of military and government ministry 
officials a largely conservative group and almost half the 
members have served more than two terms in central party bodies 
did the party have any right to expect that it the central 
committee would manifest dynamism revolutionary energy 
flexibility and exceptional thinking arguments and facts asked 
rhetorically 
gorbachev has called for the congress to trim the committee and 
transform it into a standing body that meets almost continuously 
with members chosen from the general pool of party members 
under current rules the central committee has no fixed number 
of members meets irregularly and consists of officials 
automatically included by virtue of their regular jobs 
major changes are also expected in the politburo like the 
central committee it also decides policy issues but it meets much 
more regularly it also recommends decisions to the central 
committee and sometimes makes decisions on its own 
the politburo now has 12 full and seven nonvoting members 
gorbachev has eased some conservatives off the body already and 
shifted some of its decisionmaking functions to popularly elected 
government bodies 
ligachev has complained the politburo was not consulted about 
gorbachevs controversial plans to shift the soviet economy to a 
marketoriented system or about soviet policy toward german 
unification 
the draft rules call for the politburo to be replaced by a 
presidium 
although the rules offer no details of its makeup officials 
have said the presidium would have about 30 members including the 
heads of the communist parties of the 15 soviet republics workers 
peasants intellectuals servicemen and party veterans to be 
elected by the central committee 
the proposed rules also call for splitting the general 
secretarys job now held by gorbachev into a chairman deputy 
chairman and first secretary 
it is not clear which post gorbachev will seek but he has made 
it clear he wants to retain a top party job in addition to the 
national presidency to which he was elected for a fiveyear term 
in march 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

