patrolled the streets of lusaka sunday a day after mutinous 
soldiers mounted an aborted coup to oust president kenneth kaunda 
authorities insisted repeatedly that no one was hurt saturday 
but diplomats and witnesses said at least three civilians were shot 
dead by guards near kaundas residence after they joined crowds 
celebrating his reported overthrow 
the capital and other cities and towns were calm sunday after 
five days of studentled rioting over food price increases the 
students also demanded a return to westernstyle democracy 
kaunda 67 flew back to lusaka saturday night from the central 
copperbelt province city of ndola facing the gravest political 
crisis since he led the british colony of northern rhodesia to 
independence in 1964 with promises of a better life for all 
before he left ndola a visibly shaken kaunda said he would not 
budge on his decision last month to more than double the price of 
corn meal a staple 
he also said he would consult the central committee of the 
united national independence party the only legal political 
movement in zambia since a oneparty state was imposed in 1972 on 
the fate of the coup plotters 
kaunda indicated he might act more harshly than in the past when 
his foes have been detained imprisoned or rebuked 
im beginning to ask myself whether we have been right in 
this whether we shouldnt take a different stance he said 
an army lieutenant who identified himself as mwamba luchembe of 
the signals corps was detained by soldiers at dawn saturday after 
making several broadcasts on state radio that kaunda had been 
toppled in a coup 
luchembe was being held at chamba valley high security prison 
outside lusaka government sources said he was identified as a 
member of the bembas zambias biggest tribe from the northern 
luapula province near the border with zaire 
bembas wield most economic political and military power but 
like other zambians many have become disenchanted with rising 
unemployment steep inflation and toplevel corruption 
about the same time as the broadcast troops in armored 
personnel carriers cruised lusakas streets with loudspeakers 
saying a new president had been installed 
while kaunda has referred to coup plotters since then 
official spokesmen and the government media have reported only two 
arrests 
in addition to luchembe police in ndola also placed in custody 
antigovernment activist peter bwalya for allegedly organizing 
protests after the broadcasts 
state television reported that at least two other soldiers were 
with luchembe when he made the announcements their fate was not 
known 
at least five fellow officers were detained later saturday 
security sources told the associated press they spoke on condition 
of anonymity and their report could not be independently confirmed 
the failed coup followed five days of the bloodiest urban 
violence in zambias history triggered last monday by student 
rioting 
at least 23 people were slain most of them looters according 
to officials at least 34 students were detained 
</TEXT>
