<TEXT>
two colombians wanted on us drugtrafficking 
charges have been extradited from colombia and flown to the united 
states to stand trial the us marshals service said sunday 
attorney general richard thornburgh said in a statement issued 
by the marshals office that the action demonstrates the continued 
determination of the colombian government to battle the colombian 
drug cartel and to bring these drug dealing suspects to 
justice 
the two were identified as luis carbacas 60 charged with 
leading a drug ring in north carolina and rafael juliao 42 
charged with cocaine distribution in new york city 
they are among 17 people extradited from colombia since the 
government of colombian president virgilio barco began its drive 
against the narcotics cartel last august 
carbacas and juliao were turned over to the marshals service in 
bogota on saturday evening and were flown to the united states 
early sunday morning 
carbacas was among 39 people indicted in 1985 on charges that 
included conspiracy to possess and distribute 2 million 
methaqualone tablets and more than 1000 pounds of marijuana 
he was accused with engaging in a continuing criminal enterprise 
as a ring organizer a violation of the socalled drug kingpin law 
he is to stand trial in north carolina 
juliao who is being held for arraignment in manhattan is 
charged with distributing 3 kilograms about 66 pounds of cocaine 
and conspiring to distribute 5 kilograms of cocaine 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900701-0031 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
two million moslems stood in prayer 
sunday on arafat the mount overlooking mecca where the prophet 
mohammed delivered his last sermon 14 centuries ago as the annual 
moslem pilgrimage reached its high point 
for the first time since 1986 the moslem pilgrimage called the 
hajj has been free from terrorist attacks 
only a small fire at mina the tent city five miles from arafat 
marred an otherwise calm pilgrimage season 
witnesses said that on their descent from arafat they spotted 
smoke from a distance one said they were told it was at mina but 
it did not appear to be a large blaze fire can be a danger during 
the hajj because some pilgrims bring kerosene stoves to cook in the 
tents 
terrorism blamed on iranian or shiite moslems has occurred in 
the past three years 
the worst incident was in 1987 when iranians clashed with 
security forces leading to the death of more than 400 pilgrims 
the year before the saudis confiscated large quantities of 
explosives from members of the iranian contingent 
the saudis have since set a quota of 1000 per million of 
population for each islamic nation angered by the quotas the 
iranians have boycotted the hajj since 1988 
last year some small bombs went off during the hajj killing 
one pilgrim and injuring 16 the saudis tried and convicted kuwaiti 
shiite moslems and beheaded 16 of them 
saudi authorities this year reported a growing number of 
pilgrims for the hajj the saudis said 827236 pilgrims arrived 
from around the world about 52000 more than last year and some 
30000 more than 1988 
they were joined by about half a million pilgrims from saudi 
arabia and its large expatriate community an additional half 
million people were needed for servicing tasks 
the deputy governor of mecca region prince saud ibn 
abdulmohsen who is also deputy chairman of the central hajj 
committee said the ascent of pilgrims by car and foot over the 
55mile route from mina to arafat was perfectly organized and 
the flow of traffic was very smooth 
he said a few cases of heat fatigue were reported but were not 
serious temperatures reached 111 degrees 
he said the pilgrims used umbrellas and awnings for shade and 
that 87 million flasks of iced water were distributed a pet 
project of the saudi monarch king fahd 
the stand at arafat is considered the peak of the rituals and 
anyone who misses it will not be considered to have performed hajj 
the day is spent reading the koran the moslem holy book and 
praying 
dawn prayers monday mark the start of the threeday eid aladha 
or feast of sacrifice when sheep are slaughtered by the pilgrims 
and moslems everywhere to commemorate prophet abrahams offering of 
his son to god abraham is revered by moslems as well as by jews 
and christians 
the hajj is a pillar of the islamic faith moslems who are 
healthy and can afford it are required to perform the hajj at least 
once in their lifetime 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

