a 165yearold state law requiring that 
children get a minimum share of their parents estate the only law 
of its kind in the nation was officially repealed sunday 
a parent can now disinherit a child for any reason or none 
as long as the child is over 23 and physically and mentally able to 
handle his affairs 
proponents say it was about time louisiana residents enjoy the 
right to dispose of their property as they see fit but critics 
claim that in an era of divorce and remarriage the new doctrine 
will remove an ancient protection for neglected children 
moreover they say the change will provoke intrafamily warfare 
and stir up years of litigation in the courts 
this looks like a lawyers dream and a courtrooms 
nightmare said attorney catherine soutullo 
for 165 years louisiana has carried forward the philosophy of 
frances napoleonic code demanding that children get some portion 
of their parents estate 
one child was guaranteed at least a fourth two or more shared 
at least half parents could cut their children off for only 12 
reasons ranging from failing to ransom parents from captivity to 
failing to communicate with a parent for two years 
tulane law school professor cynthia samuel said the new law will 
expose state courts to ugly lawsuits by children trying to 
invalidate a will on grounds that a beneficiary unduly influenced 
the parent 
she also predicted more people would make wills which they must 
do to take advantage of their new power to disinherit 
youd be amazed how much interest there is out there among 
