<TEXT>
monika pein mailed a letter to a 
friend in the united states sunday describing the incredible pace 
of events in the two germanys and stamped it with a commemorative 
imprint from the post office 
i have just written in the letter that i really cannot grasp 
that we germany will again be together said mrs pein who was 
born near what is now wroclaw poland her husband was born in east 
germany near halle 
we think about this every day i really cannot believe this 
she said i had not thought that in my life im over 50 i 
would live to see this 
chancellor helmut kohl called the economic merger of the two 
germanys that took effect sunday the decisive step on the way to 
the unity of our fatherland a big day in the history of the german 
nation 
but not everyone shared the enthusiasm and the day marking the 
first and most difficult step to unification passed with little 
fanfare in this west german capital 
the post office kept special hours so people could have their 
mail stamped with an oval commemorative imprint noting july 1 as 
the day economic monetary and social union between east germany 
and west germany took effect 
but a postal worker said it was publicized too late to attract 
many people and only about 80 people had stopped by in the first 
few hours 
reaction among west germans to the economic merger with east 
germany and eventual full unification was varied some like mrs 
pein are realizing a dream others say it is happening too fast 
and worry what it could cost still others especially younger 
people feel little kinship with their brothers to the east 
manfred brocker a 43yearold native of bonn who says hes 
documented political changes over the years with stamps collected 
one more for this historic day but had mixed feelings 
basically its good he said of the economic merger and 
upcoming unification but people are only talking about east 
germany and not at all about the west germans nobody knows what it 
will cost us or if it will be good with the currency 
one worries that its happening much too fast he said 
complaining there was too little information from the government 
over what problems might result 
and he was also not sure how alike the germans were after 40 
years of separation 
its a completely different generation he said perhaps 
in 20 years the differences will be blurred he said but not 
so fast 
detlef bloss born in weimar the small east german town that 
was capital of germanys first attempt at representative democracy 
said he was worried a catastrophe in east germany could result 
because of the large numbers of expected unemployed 
experts have predicted that anywhere from 500000 to 4 million 
east germans could lose their jobs as state subsidies fall to a 
market economy onethird of all businesses are not expected to 
survive 
i dont know that its right its all so sudden said 
bloss who fled to west germany in 1978 the mentality is 
different and the two economic systems are different 
the people in east germany are very greedy toward western 
money but they dont know what the future will bring that is the 
problem that is the worry i have 
</TEXT>
